            <h1 id='getting-started'>Getting Started</h1>
            <h4>FIRST THINGS FIRST</h4>
            <p>Once you have included the Dresssed gem in your Gemfile, along with its custom source, and run <code>bundle install</code>, you're almost done. The first thing is to run the main generator by executing <code>rails g dresssed:install</code> (note the three 's' in 'dresssed'!). You will be prompted if anything will be overwritten, and if you're not sure say no and double check first that you won't overwrite anything you need.</p>

            <h4>LETS MAKE A GORGEOUS DASHBOARD IN 10 SECONDS</h4>
            <p>If you want to see what else you can run next, take a look at the <a href="#generators">Code Generators</a> section below, or run the command <code>bundle exec rails g | grep 'dresssed'</code> in your terminal. A fun thing to run next might be the dashboard geneartor since it will give you something nice to look at. First we need to generate the <strong>SideNav</strong> layout: <code>bundle exec rails g dresssed:sidenav home sidenav</code> - this will generate the SideNav layout and add the <code>layout 'sidenav'</code> directive to the <code>HomeController</code>.</p>
            <p>Next, we'll generate the Dashboard view itself: <code>bundle exec rails g dresssed:dashboard home dashboard</code> - this will generate the Dashboard view on the <code>home</code> controller under the <code>dashboard</code> action. Don't foget to add a Route in your <code>config/routes.rb</code> for the dashboard. Once you've dont that, and you hit the URL for the dashboard you should be greeted with something that looks like this: </p>
            <img src='/dashboard.png' class='thumbnail text-center'/>
            <p>Pretty nice, eh? </p>

